{"id":"merritt-parkway","generatedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z","designation":"National Scenic Byway","parkCode":null,"source":{"roadArticle":"Merritt Parkway","revisionId":1361562016,"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Merritt_Parkway"},"attribution":{"license":"CC BY-SA 4.0","licenseUrl":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","articleUrl":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Merritt_Parkway","text":"Route, junction, and history details adapted from the Wikipedia article \"Merritt Parkway\", by Wikipedia contributors, licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0."},"sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia","src":"wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Merritt_Parkway","revisionId":1361562016,"retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"},{"name":"Federal Highway Administration — National Scenic Byways","src":"fhwa","url":"https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways","retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"},{"name":"OpenStreetMap contributors (ODbL)","src":"osm","url":"https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright","retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"}],"endpoints":{"from":"Greenwich, CT","to":"Milford, CT","via":["New Canaan, CT","Westport, CT","Trumbull, CT"]},"itinerary":[{"seq":1,"place":"Greenwich","state":"CT","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":0,"toNextMi":8.9,"note":"The drive begins here","control":["New York City Route 15 begins","Armonk","NY","Round Hill Road","Lake Avenue","Butternut Hollow Road","North Street"],"lat":41.24637,"lng":-73.08897,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":2,"place":"Stamford","state":"CT","kind":"town","mileFromStart":8.9,"toNextMi":4.3,"note":"Junction toward Den Road","control":["Den Road"],"lat":41.1017,"lng":-73.56869,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":3,"place":"New Canaan","state":"CT","kind":"town","mileFromStart":13.2,"toNextMi":2.8,"note":"","control":["New Canaan","Darien"],"lat":41.12399,"lng":-73.47238,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":4,"place":"Norwalk","state":"CT","kind":"town","mileFromStart":16,"toNextMi":4.7,"note":"Junction toward Norwalk & Danbury","control":["Norwalk","Danbury"],"lat":41.13823,"lng":-73.44231,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":5,"place":"Westport","state":"CT","kind":"town","mileFromStart":20.7,"toNextMi":6.3,"note":"Junction toward Westport & Wilton","control":["Westport","Wilton","Weston"],"lat":41.16354,"lng":-73.35952,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":6,"place":"Fairfield","state":"CT","kind":"town","mileFromStart":27,"toNextMi":2.3,"note":"Junction toward Fairfield & Redding","control":["Fairfield","Redding","Easton"],"lat":41.17987,"lng":-73.31323,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":7,"place":"Trumbull","state":"CT","kind":"town","mileFromStart":29.3,"toNextMi":7.2,"note":"Junction toward Park Avenue","control":["Park Avenue","Bridgeport","Danbury","Trumbull","Waterbury"],"lat":null,"lng":null,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":8,"place":"Stratford","state":"CT","kind":"town","mileFromStart":36.5,"toNextMi":1,"note":"Junction toward Stratford & Shelton","control":["Stratford","Shelton"],"lat":null,"lng":null,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":9,"place":"Housatonic River","state":"CT","kind":"crossing","mileFromStart":37.5,"toNextMi":0.2,"note":"Crosses Igor I. Sikorsky Memorial Bridge","control":["Igor I. Sikorsky Memorial Bridge"],"lat":41.23853,"lng":-73.12765,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":10,"place":"Milford","state":"CT","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":37.7,"toNextMi":null,"note":"The drive ends here","control":["Milford","New London","Hartford"],"lat":41.04601,"lng":-73.66977,"src":"wikipedia"}],"history":{"paragraphs":["The Merritt Parkway is one of the oldest scenic parkways in the United States. The portion from Greenwich to Norwalk was opened on June 29, 1938. The section from Norwalk to Trumbull was completed in November 1939, and in 1940, it was finished to the Housatonic River in Stratford. The parkway was named for U.S. Congressman Schuyler Merritt, who was instrumental in enacting legislation allowing the parkway to be built. The Merritt Parkway is the first leg of what later became modern Route 15. Built between 1934 and 1940, the Merritt Parkway runs for 37 miles (60 km) from the New York state line in Greenwich to the Housatonic River in Stratford. It was conceived as a way to alleviate congestion on the Boston Post Road (U.S. Route 1) in Fairfield County.","After the parkway fully opened in 1940, travelers commonly stopped to picnic along the side of the road. The Merritt Parkway Advisory Commission (later the Merritt Parkway Advisory Committee) decided to ban horses and buggies, bicycles, pedestrians, billboards, and U-turns, while a system of horse trails along the parkway was developed, but later abandoned. To ease objections from county residents, who feared an influx of New Yorkers on their roads, in their towns, on their beaches, and through their forests, highway planners called on engineers, landscape architects, and architects to create a safe and aesthetically pleasing limited-access highway, one with exit and entrance ramps, but no intersections, that would not spoil the countryside. The bridges played a prominent role in the design. Architect George L. Dunkelberger designed them all. They reflected the popularity of the Art Deco style, with touches of neoclassical and modern design. Some of these bridges were constructed by the Works Progress Administration.","In 1948, the road was signed as part of Connecticut Route 15. Originally, the road had the unsigned designation of Connecticut Route 1A. Also around this time, exit numbers were posted on the road. In December 1949, a connection to the Wilber Cross Parkway was opened to traffic.","In 1955, exit 30 (not to be confused with the new exit 30), an at-grade intersection with Butternut Hollow Road that crossed traffic in both directions, was permanently closed. It had already been declared a safety hazard."],"sourceSection":"History","src":"wikipedia"},"highlights":[{"n":"Greenwich","d":"The drive begins here","q":"Greenwich","lat":41.04722222,"lng":-73.62222222,"src":"wikipedia"},{"n":"Housatonic River","d":"Crosses Igor I. Sikorsky Memorial Bridge","q":"Housatonic River","lat":41.16916667,"lng":-73.10833333,"src":"wikipedia"},{"n":"Milford","d":"The drive ends here","q":"Milford","lat":41.22416667,"lng":-73.05972222,"src":"wikipedia"}],"references":[{"n":1,"text":"Connecticut Department of Transportation (2012). \"2012 Traffic Volumes, State Maintained Highway Network\" (PDF). Connecticut Department of Transportation. Archived from the original (PDF) on January 27, 2020. Retrieved January 27, 2020.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20200127225912/https://portal.ct.gov/-/media/DOT/documents/dpolicy/traflog/TrafficLog12pdf.pdf"},{"n":2,"text":"\"What is allowed to travel on the Merritt Parkway?\". Connecticut Department of Transportation. Archived from the original on November 3, 2017. Retrieved August 24, 2007.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20171103015419/http://www.ct.gov/dot/cwp/view.asp?A=2137&Q=294976"},{"n":3,"text":"\"National Register Information System\". National Register of Historic Places. National Park Service. January 23, 2007.","url":"https://npgallery.nps.gov/NRHP"},{"n":4,"text":"\"Connecticut: Fairfield County Historic Places\". National Register of Historic Places. Archived from the original on August 17, 2017. Retrieved August 24, 2007.","url":"http://www.nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com/CT/Fairfield/districts.html"},{"n":5,"text":"Shannahan, John W. (April 17, 1991). \"National Register of Historic Places in America\". Retrieved March 14, 2020. National Park Service Certification I, hereby, certify that this property is: entered in the National Register [signed Beth L. Savage] 4-17-91[...]The Merritt Parkway","url":"https://npgallery.nps.gov/GetAsset/96eb4fba-acde-4e35-be75-4016e832b170#page=81"},{"n":6,"text":"\"America's 11 Most Endangered Historic Places\". National Trust for Historic Preservation. Archived from the original on May 22, 2010. Retrieved May 23, 2010.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20100522153049/http://www.preservationnation.org/travel-and-sites/sites/northeast-region/merritt-parkway.html"},{"n":7,"text":"Lynn, Catherine; Wigren, Christopher (February 22, 1991). \"National Register of Historic Places Registration Form: Merritt Parkway\" (PDF). National Park Service. Retrieved February 12, 2015. Photos","url":"https://npgallery.nps.gov/NRHP/GetAsset/NRHP/91000410_text"},{"n":8,"text":"\"Steel Structure\" (PDF). Connecticut Department of Transportation. Archived from the original (PDF) on February 21, 2017. Retrieved July 12, 2018.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20170221185858/http://www.ct.gov/dot/lib/dot/documents/dpublications/highway/Chapter_13.pdf"}],"routeLine":[[41.24637,-73.08897],[41.24612,-73.09556],[41.24606,-73.09713],[41.24601,-73.0979],[41.24589,-73.09897],[41.2457,-73.10007],[41.24549,-73.10103],[41.24514,-73.10241],[41.24438,-73.10512],[41.24407,-73.10617],[41.24365,-73.10769],[41.24328,-73.10893],[41.24303,-73.10982],[41.241,-73.11696],[41.24045,-73.11894],[41.23995,-73.12089],[41.23964,-73.1222],[41.23937,-73.12341],[41.23902,-73.12505],[41.23853,-73.12765],[41.2381,-73.13034],[41.2379,-73.13165],[41.23774,-73.13305],[41.23748,-73.13525],[41.23736,-73.13638],[41.23726,-73.13766],[41.23717,-73.13878],[41.2371,-73.13987],[41.23701,-73.14129],[41.23696,-73.14255],[41.2369,-73.14494],[41.23689,-73.14764],[41.23693,-73.14953],[41.23701,-73.15152],[41.23709,-73.15308],[41.23715,-73.15395],[41.23743,-73.15747],[41.23769,-73.15996],[41.23778,-73.16087],[41.23787,-73.16225],[41.23784,-73.16325],[41.23777,-73.16415],[41.23765,-73.16508],[41.23736,-73.16624],[41.23707,-73.1674],[41.23681,-73.16839],[41.23664,-73.16926],[41.23659,-73.17018],[41.23668,-73.17109],[41.2368,-73.17233],[41.2369,-73.17327],[41.23699,-73.1742],[41.23724,-73.17643],[41.23732,-73.17748],[41.23731,-73.17843],[41.23723,-73.1793],[41.23706,-73.1806],[41.23696,-73.18137],[41.23677,-73.18267],[41.2366,-73.18414],[41.23638,-73.18573],[41.23625,-73.1866],[41.23611,-73.18745],[41.23597,-73.18831],[41.23569,-73.19017],[41.235